result.execSummary:
Brita Jane Britt was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Brita Jane Britt was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Copy of Criminal complaint and waiver of extradition mailed to Governor's office.
This did not take place. Court event needs to be in court record to dispose of case.

11:52 AM Defendant Brita Jane Britt appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Halle Hatch in court for State of Wisconsin. Attorney Derek Sanders appeared via phone. Court goes over extradition process to Ms. Britt. Court informs Defendant of charges, possible penalties and constitutional rights. Atty Sanders explains waiving extradition is a faster/easier process.  Defendant waives her right to extradition. Defendant signs the waiver. Court will sign waiver when it's presented. 11:59
